'''No. 410 Squadron RCAF''', the "Cougars", is a [[Canadian Forces Air Command]] aircraft squadron currently located at [[Canada]]'s primary [[CF-18]] training base, [[Cold Lake, Alberta|Cold Lake]], [[Alberta]]. The squadron was formed during the [[Second World War]] as a [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] squadron, but was originally under the [[Royal Air Force]]. The first official sortie occurred on 23 July 1941 when Pilot Officer Lucas was flying his Defiant V1183. During the Second World War it was credited as being the top night fighter squadron in the [[RAF Second Tactical Air Force]] (TAF) during the period between [[D-Day]] and [[VE-Day]].

During the Second World War No. 410 Squadron RCAF flew in major operations such as the [[D-Day|Normandy Landings]] and the [[Battle of the Bulge]]. Between these two battles the squadron flew nightly patrols and many members gained ace status. Two members of 410, Flight Lieutenant (F/L) Currie and Flight Officer (F/O) Rose, were the first members of the RCAF to see the German [[V-2]] Rocket Bomb in flight, later that same rocket bomb landed on the British coast.

The squadron was also disbanded in 1964 but was reformed in 1968 and remains active. The squadron trains the most people a year on the CF-18 as 410 Tactical Fighter (Operational Training) Squadron. The TV show [[Jetstream (TV series)|''Jetstream'']] was filmed with the squadron and showed life on the base and what pilots must endure to become [[fighter pilot]]s.

== Formation and badge ==
No. 410 Squadron was formed at [[RAF Ayr]] in June 1941 as a [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] "[[Article XV squadron]]", under [[Royal Air Force]] operational control, the third night fighter squadron in the RCAF. At the time it was equipped with the [[Boulton Paul Defiant]]. In May 1942 these were removed from service to have the  [[Bristol Beaufighter]]s be introduced, and in October of the same year these were replaced with [[De Havilland Mosquito]] Mk II's, with which the first victory for the squadron was claimed. No. 410 was at the time noted as being the top-scoring night-fighter unit in [[RAF Second Tactical Air Force]] in the period between [[D-Day]] and [[VE Day]],<ref name="RCAF">{{cite web|url=http://www.rcaf.com/squadrons/400series/410squadron.php |title= Royal Canadian Air Force - 410 Squadron |accessdate=13 December 2008}}</ref> although there are other claims that the top-scoring night-fighter unit is really [[No. 409 Squadron RCAF]], on the basis that there were many victories quickly counted up during 1943.<ref name=MAWW2-4>Thomas, 42</ref> 

The No. 410 Squadron badge depicts a cougar's face with a background decrescent (waning moon). The cougar, a North American mammal, was chosen because of its speed and power in its attacks. The waning moon refers to the squadron's night operations.<ref name="4Wing"/> The two major devices are in reference to the Second World War fighter days, where the squadron was a night fighting unit that was known for its skill and score. The squadron's motto is ''Noctivaga'', which means "wandering by night".<ref name="4Wing"/>

== Second World War ==
[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 101I-363-2258-11, Flugzeug Junkers Ju 88.jpg|right|thumb|A Junkers Ju88 in flight, similar to the ones that were shot down by No. 410 Squadron]]
=== Bases ===
No. 410 Squadron RCAF began its career in the Second World War at RAF Ayr, which was located at Ayrshire. From there it was moved to [[RAF Drem]], located at East Lothian, but was returned to RAF Ayr 10 months later. On 1 September 1942 the Cougars were again moved, this time to [[RAF Scorton]], in Yorkshire, but just under two months later was relocated to [[RAF Acklington]]. Although the Squadron moved three times in 1942, it was relocated four times in 1943 and later, five times in 1944.<ref name="Command"/> In 1943 they were placed at [[RAF Coleby Grange]], but this would not be the first time. For the sixth time the Squadron was moved, this time to [[RAF West Malling]], but being re-equipped with Mosquito VI from the former Mosquito II. 8 November 1943 the Squadron was placed at [[RAF Hunsdon]], the first of three times at RAF Hundson, but a mere month later it was moved to RAF Castle Camps. Only four months later, and four months into 1944, were the Cougars relocated back to RAF Hundson, this for the second time.<ref name="Command"/> On 18 June 1944, they were placed at [[RAF Zeals]], only to be moved again in one month and ten days to [[RAF Colerne]], in Wiltshire. On 9 September 1944 No. 410 Squadron RCAF was again, this for the third and final time, moved to RAF Hunsdon. 13 days later, the squadron was relocated back to their sixth base, RAF Coleby Grange.<ref name="Command">{{cite web|url=http://www.rafcommands.currantbun.com/Fighter/410F.html |title= No. 410 (Cougar) Squadron RCAF |accessdate=1 March 2009}}</ref> On 3 November 1944 the Squadron moved to RAF Amiens-Glisy, for the first of two times. Only two months later the squadron was relocated to RAF Lille-Vendeville, the first movement of the squadron in 1945.<ref name="History"/> As of 5 April 1945 the Cougars were located at RAF Amiens-Glisy, the second deployment to that area. The final movement of the war occurred on 9 June 1945, when the squadron moved to RAF Gilze-Rijen.<ref name="History">{{cite web|url=http://www.historyofwar.org/air/units/RCAF/410_wwII.html |title= No. 410 'Cougar' Squadron (RCAF) |accessdate=1 March 2009}}</ref>

=== Operations ===
On 23 July 1941, [[Pilot Officer]] (P/O) Lucas flew his Defiant V1183 from Ayr for the first official operation of the war for No. 410 Squadron RCAF. The first enemy contact, however, occurred on 6/7 September 1942, when a Beaufighter II from [[RAF Scorton]] flown by P/O R.R. Ferguson and P/O D. Creed (navigator), intercepted a Luftwaffe [[Ju88]]. The Beaufighter was vectored to the Ju88 approximately 20 miles north east of [[Whitby]]. The attack damaged the Ju88.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documentsonline/details-result.asp?Edoc_Id=7748377|title=Combat Reports, Second World War<U+2014>Image details<U+2014>Ferguson, R R, 06 September 1942|work=DocumentsOnline|publisher=[[The National Archives]]|format=fee required to view full pdf of original combat report|accessdate=15 December 2008}}</ref>  Since they did not manage to destroy the aircraft, this not count as the squadron's first outright victory.  That came on 22 January 1943, when [[Flight Sergeant]] B.M. Haight and [[Sergeant]] T. Kipling (RAF, observer), flying a Mosquito II from Acklington, were credited with a [[Dornier Do 217|Do 217]], which was destroyed near [[Hartlepool]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documentsonline/details-result.asp?Edoc_Id=7748398|title=Combat Reports, Second World War<U+2014>Image details<U+2014>Haight, B M, 22 January 1943|work=DocumentsOnline|publisher=[[The National Archives]]|format=fee required to view full pdf of original combat report|accessdate=15 December 2008}}</ref> This occurred because of "night readiness", the ability to fly at a moment's notice at night. By the end of the war a total of 75<U+00BE> victories had been claimed.<ref name="AWFA">{{cite web| title=No. 410 Squadron | publisher=All Weather Fighter Association | url =http://www.allwxfighters.ca/410squadron.htm | accessdate =03 June 2008}}</ref> The squadron flew 2,972 [[sortie]]s and accumulated 28,150 hours of flight time. The squadron's victories included 75<U+00BE> destroyed, 2 probably destroyed, and 9 damaged. The squadron had the following casualties: operational: 17 aircraft and 32 aircrew, of whom 10 were killed, 20 presumed dead, and two were made prisoners of war. Non-operational: 14 aircraft and 30 personnel, of whom 29 were killed, 1 injured.<ref name="AWFA"/><br style="clear:both;"/>

==== D-Day and the invasion of Europe ====
Between November 1943 and May 1944, the squadron was engaged in the night defence of Britain. On 5 June 1944, No. 410 Squadron's CO, [[Wing Commander (rank)|Wing Commander]] G.A. Hiltz, flew a four-aircraft detachment to [[Colerne]] where they provided fighter cover for the initial airborne landings. Among the pilots who flew that operation was Flight Lieutenant Charles Emanuel "Pop" Edinger, who would later become a [[flying ace|ace]]. On the night prior to the 6 June 1944 invasion (D-Day), all of the TAF's night fighter squadrons were working late to ensure safety for the landing force. During June 1944, 18 of the 22 fighters were available for the flight. At 01:00 the first of four patrols took off, but the patrol was uneventful, with the pilots reporting clouds at 10,000 feet.<ref name=MAWW2-1>Thomas, 26</ref> A further five patrols were flown to help cover the 4,000 ships that were part of [[Operation Neptune]]. On 7 June two of the aircraft were fired upon by friendly [[Avro Lancaster|Lancaster Bombers]], who assumed they were hostile. However No. 410 Squadron claimed its first kill, when [[Flying Officer]]s A. Mcleod and Bob Snowdon destroyed a [[Junkers]] [[Junkers Ju 188|Ju188]]. On 12 June the squadron claimed multiple bomber kills.<ref name=MAWW2-1/> The "little [[The Blitz|blitz]]" was moving in full on England. The Cougars shot down 14 raiders with five more probably destroyed or damaged. But the success was overshadowed by the allied invasion Europe. From June to August 1944, the squadron's history was mostly taken up with patrols nightly over the beachheads to guard the Allied troops and shipping against enemy bombers. Thirty-one times No. 410's Mosquitoes brought down their opponent and damaged or destroyed three more. Then the squadron moved to France and in the next eight months added 25 "kills" and a "damaged" to its score.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rcaf.com/439squadron/410sqn/410eng1-1.htm |title=RCAF - History of No. 410 Squadron |accessdate=24 January 2009}}</ref>

==== Post D-Day ====

[[File:Dornier Do217E.jpg|thumb|right|A Dornier Do.217 that is similar to ones that were shot down by No. 410 Squadron RCAF]]
The squadron was flying patrols and was getting many kills. In one instance Warrant Officer (W/O) W.F. Price and P/O J.G. Costello had shot down two Do.217 aircraft in twenty minutes. Since D-Day the Cougars had destroyed twelve enemy bombers. It was another five days before the squadron scored another kill. In the interval the crews, still maintaining their nine sorties a night schedule, had little to report. One night an engine in W/C Hiltz<U+2019>s Mosquito failed on the take-off run and the aircraft, swerving off the runway, crashed into "A" Flight dispersal. The crews escaped injury, but many buildings went up in flames.<ref name="HIST4"/> During an operation that resulted in the thirteenth kill, one aircraft crashed and its occupants never made it out. For the next week the weather was poor, restricting night operations. Most of the crews that did go out had to be diverted to other bases on their return. Enemy activity had also diminished and the beachhead was much quieter than it had been in mid-June. On the first two nights in July there were no sorties at all. Then the weather improved and the nightly round of nine patrols was resumed.<ref name="HIST4"/>

F/L Currie and F/O Rose were the first to see the [[V-2]] Rocket bomb, on the night of 10/11 September. While on patrol from Brussels to Antwerp and Rotterdam they saw a bright orange light dead ahead and seemingly at their own level, 10,000 feet. At first glance Currie paid no attention to it, taking it for a bright star. Suddenly, Currie said, "it began to climb <U+2013> hell it climbed!" The light appeared to go straight up, so rapidly that within a few seconds it had passed out of sight. On return to base the crew reported the sighting as a [[V-1 flying bomb]], but their account of the spectacular rate of climb and other details aroused great interest at higher levels. That night, a few moments after Currie and Rose made their sighting, a V-2 crashed on the English coast. Two nights later F/Os Fullerton and Gallagher also saw a ball of yellow flame streak vertically into the night sky, and in the weeks that followed there were many more similar reports.<ref name="HIST4"/>

==== Battle of the Bulge and end of war ====
During the battle all of the TAF, including No. 410 Squadron, was on 48 hour alert. In the middle of the month of December, under dreadful weather conditions, the Germans launched a surprise offensive on the [[Battle of the Bulge|Ardennes]], also using the Luftwaffe, which caught many squadrons off guard. No. 410 Squadron enjoyed a number of successes, some of them even on Christmas day.<ref name=MAWW2-2/> Although the war was entering its final stages, the squadron had to watch out for flak. The fighter squadrons continued to make advances until February while waiting for the Canadian push through the [[Reichwald]] on the Rhine to take place. Although there was some aerial fighting, the major fighting with the Luftwaffe occurred when the Canadians started to cross the Rhine on 24 March 1945.<ref name=MAWW2-4>{{cite book |title= Mosquito Aces of World War 2 |last=Thomas |first=Andrew |coauthors=Davey, Chris |year=2005 |publisher=Osprey Publishing |isbn= 1841768782|page=41 |url= http://books.google.ca/books?id=M3FURgZ0qu4C&pg=PA41&dq=No.+410+Squadron#PPA41,M1}}</ref>

On the evening of 18 December, during the Battle of the Bulge, Edinger was vectored to a Ju87, which Edinger then fired upon. His navigator, C.C. Vaessen, confirmed the kill stating that it had been on fire, having been hit in the starboard engine. The Ju87 crashed into the trees and was engulfed in flame.<ref name=MAWW2-2>Thomas, 39</ref><ref name=EdingerReport /> During the final months of the war Flight Lieutenant Rayne Schultz claimed his fifth kill of the war after having returned from working at the Training Command. His fifth kill was a Ju188, which he claimed on 13/14 February 1944.<ref>{{cite web |title=National Archives - Rayne Schultz Combat Report |url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documentsonline/search-results.asp?searchtype=browserefine&query=last_name%3dschultz|scope%3d410|scope%3d410&catid=27&pagenumber=1&querytype=1&mediaarray=* |accessdate=09 February 2009}}</ref> Shortly afterwards he claimed a second Ju188 on 10/11 April 1945. He claimed his final kills on 21/22 April 1945 by downing two Ju88s near Ferrbellen.<ref name=MAWW2-4/>

A few days after the Squadron moved to Lille/Vendeville it was called upon to provide a special patrol of four aircraft as air cover for [[Armistice Day]] ceremonies being held in Paris; no enemy intruders attempted to intervene. Later in the month there was a tragic accident at base which took the lives of two pilots who had joined the Cougars a short time previously. F/Os H. Connelly and J. Hunt had gone up together to practice circuits and landings. As they made a circuit, preparatory to landing, the Mosquito stalled and crashed from 500 feet. A few days before Christmas there was another disaster, the heaviest blow suffered by the squadron throughout its long career.<ref name="HIST4">{{cite web |url=http://www.rcaf.com/439squadron/410sqn/410eng1-4.htm |title=RCAF - History of No. 410 Squadron |accessdate=24 January 2009}}</ref> For several days the airfield had been fogbound. When the sky cleared somewhat in the afternoon of the 21st, S/L Fulton, "B<U+201D> Flight commander, took off for England in the Squadron [[Airspeed Oxford|Oxford]]. With him were three officers and two airmen, all going on leave. Near Wrotham, Kent, the aircraft for some reason crashed and only one of its occupants survived, seriously injured. Killed with S/L Fulton were his navigator F/O A.R. Ayton (RAF), who had accompanied him on posting to the Cougars in October, F/L F.G. Thomson, DFC (RAF), who had arrived late in November to begin a second tour, and LACs E. Wahlers and R. Seefried. F/O W. Rumbold, another RAF navigator, was the injured passenger; he had been with the Squadron for two months.<ref name="HIST4"/> The squadron was disbanded with the end of the war on 9 June 1945.<ref name="AWFA"/>

=== Wartime commanders ===
The first commanding officer was Squadron Leader P.Y. Davoud, who was in charge between 30 June 1941 and 4 September 1941. Following his time as commander was Wing Commander (W/C) M. Lipton, who was in charge between 5 September 1941 and 30 July 1942. This position was then given to W/C F.W. Hillock, who was in charge between 19 August 1942 and 19 May 1943, when the position was given to W/C G.H. Elms, who was in charge between 20 May 1943 and 18 February 1944. In the latter part of the war W/C G.A. Hiltz, who was in charge between 19 February 1944 and 1 April 1945, was given command, and the last commander of the war was W/C E.P. Heybroek, who was in charge between 2 April 1945 and 9 June 1945.<ref name="AWFA"/>

