[[File:Distinguished Flying Cross and bar.jpg|thumb|right|A DFC with bar]]
==== Individual awards ====
At least 12 members of the squadron were decorated during the war, with the award of 11 [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Crosses]] (DFC), plus one [[medal bar|bar]] to the DFC, and a [[Distinguished Flying Medal]] (DFM). The first DFCs went to Acting [[Flight Lieutenant]] Martin Anthony Cybulski and [[Flying Officer]] Harold Herbert Ladbrook on 9 November 1943<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=36241|supp=yes|startpage=4918|date=5 November 1943|accessdate=15 December 2008}}</ref> The citation does not mention that they had to return to base on a single engine, and with other damage to the aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documentsonline/details-result.asp?Edoc_Id=7748370|title=Combat Reports, Second World War<U+2014>Image details<U+2014>Ladbrook, H H, 27 March 1943; 26 September 1943|work=DocumentsOnline|publisher=[[The National Archives]]|format=fee required to view full pdf of original combat reports|accessdate=15 December 2008}}</ref> This was followed by Flying Officers Rayne Dennis Schultz and Vernon Albert Williams on 14 January 1944.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=36329|supp=yes|startpage=285|date=11 January 1944|accessdate=15 December 2008}}</ref> Again, the citation does not mention the severe damage to their own aircraft. At the close of the action with the third Do 217, which the combat report describes as: "a long duel with the enemy pilot showing a high degree of airmanship," they were hit by return fire, with a cannon shell destroying much of the instrument panel, and narrowly missing the pilot. The starboard engine almost died, then recovered, but then the port engine caught fire. They managed to return to [[RAF Bradwell]] on the starboard engine, landing at 19:45 on 10 December 1943.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documentsonline/details-result.asp?Edoc_Id=7748440|title=Combat Reports, Second World War<U+2014>Image details<U+2014>Williams, V A, 15 August 1943; 10 December 1943|work=DocumentsOnline|publisher=[[The National Archives]]|format=fee required to view full pdf of original combat reports|accessdate=15 December 2008}}</ref>

Sergeant James Norman was awarded the DFM on 26 September 1944.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=36718|supp=yes|startpage=4444|endpage=4445|date=22 September 1944|accessdate=15 December 2008}}</ref> [[Squadron Leader]] James Dean Somerville and F/O George Douglas Robinson were also awarded the DFC on 20 October 1944.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=36756|supp=yes|startpage=4813|date=17 October 1944|accessdate=15 December 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documentsonline/details-result.asp?Edoc_Id=7748434|title=Combat Reports, Second World War<U+2014>Image details<U+2014>Robinson, G D, 13 February 1944; 06 August 1944, 01 August 1944, 14 August 1944|work=DocumentsOnline|publisher=[[The National Archives]]|format=fee required to view full pdf of original combat reports|accessdate=15 December 2008}}</ref> Then F/L Charles Emanuel Edinger on 5 December 1944, for destroying four [[Junkers Ju 88]], and one unidentified German aircraft between June and October. He subsequently claimed one further Ju 88 and one [[Junkers Ju 87]] in December.<ref name=EdingerReport>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documentsonline/details-result.asp?Edoc_Id=7748373|title=Combat Reports, Second World War<U+2014>Image details<U+2014>Edinger, C E, 16 September 1944; 06 October 1944, 24 December 1944, 14 June 1944, 03 July 1944, 16 September 1944, 18 June 1944, 18 December 1944|work=DocumentsOnline|publisher=[[The National Archives]]|format=fee required to view full pdf of original combat reports|accessdate=15 December 2008}}</ref><ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=36826|supp=yes|startpage=5577|endpage=5578|date=1 December 1944|accessdate=15 December 2008}}</ref>

Flight Lieutenants Ben Erwin Plumer and William Warren Hargrove also received the DFC on 15 December 1944 for shooting down a [[Messerschmitt Bf 110]] on 6 October:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documentsonline/details-result.asp?Edoc_Id=7748422|title=Combat Reports, Second World War<U+2014>Image details<U+2014>Hargrove, W W, 06 October 1944|work=DocumentsOnline|publisher=[[The National Archives]]|format=fee required to view full pdf of original combat report|accessdate=15 December 2008}}</ref><ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=36839|supp=yes|startpage=5737|date=12 December 1944|accessdate=15 December 2008}}</ref> F/O Dennis George Tongue was awarded the DFC on 29 December 1944,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=36863|supp=yes|startpage=5954|endpage=5955|date=26 December 1944|accessdate=15 December 2008}}</ref> and a [[medal bar|bar]] to his DFC on 2 March 1945.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=36964|supp=yes|startpage=1205|date=27 February 1945|accessdate=15 December 2008}}</ref> Tongue was a member of the RAF, and had been commissioned from sergeant, before his promotion to flying officer. His pilot on 25 November 1944, the night he won the bar to his DFC, was A. A. Harrington of the [[United States Army Air Force]]. The three aircraft they destroyed were Ju 88s, their own Mosquito was hit by debris from the second Ju 88, and during the fight that led to the downing of the third, Tongue was also having to keep track of a further Ju 88 which was endeavouring to attack them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documentsonline/details-result.asp?Edoc_Id=7748403|title=Combat Reports, Second World War<U+2014>Image details<U+2014>Tongue, Dennis G, 14 March 1944; 19 June 1944, 26 September 1944, 29 October 1944, 25 November 1944|work=DocumentsOnline|publisher=[[The National Archives]]|format=fee required to view full pdf of original combat report|accessdate=15 December 2008}}</ref>

F/O Donald Murdo Mackenzie was awarded the DFC on 27 February 1945,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=36959|supp=yes|startpage=1134|endpage=1135|date=23 February 1945|accessdate=15 December 2008}}</ref> he had destroyed a Ju 88 on 30 July 1944, and two more in a single sortie on 24 December.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documentsonline/details-result.asp?Edoc_Id=7748364|title=Combat Reports, Second World War<U+2014>Image details<U+2014>MacKenzie, D, 30 July 1944; 29 December 1944|work=DocumentsOnline|publisher=[[The National Archives]]|format=fee required to view full pdf of original combat report|accessdate=15 December 2008}}</ref>

== Post-World War Two ==
[[File:Cf101 borden 1.jpg|thumb|right|A [[CF-101 Voodoo]]]]
No. 410 Squadron was reactivated on 1 December 1946 as an [[Air Defence]] squadron flying [[de Havilland Vampire]] F.3 aircraft, and was re-formed from a defence role into that of a fighter role at St Hubert (Montreal), Quebec on 1 December 1948. The squadron later converted to [[Canadair Sabre]]s and was deployed to Europe, flying from [[RAF North Luffenham|RCAF Station North Luffenham]] in the UK and [[RCAF Station Marville]] in France until the squadron was replaced by [[No. 445 Squadron RCAF|No. 445 Squadron]] in 1956. The squadron was the first postwar Regular Force fighter unit to fly Vampire and Sabre aircraft, and the first to join No. 1 (Fighter) Wing of No. 1 Air Division Europe.<ref name="RCAF"/><ref name="AWFA"/> When No. 445 All Weather (Fighter) [AW(F)] Squadron arrived from Canada, No. 410 was deactivated at Marville on 1 October 1956 and reactivated as an all-weather fighter squadron at [[RCAF Station Uplands|Uplands]] (Ottawa), Ontario on 1 November, flying [[Avro Canada CF-100]]s. The CF-100s were removed from service and, in December 1961, the [[CF-101 Voodoo]] interceptors, were introduced for [[North American Aerospace Defense Command|North American air defence]]. The squadron continued to fly Voodoos until defence cuts led to the squadron being deactivated. On 31 March 1964, the Cougars held their final parade, and at midnight No. 410 Squadron ceased to exist. In 1968, No. 3 OTU (Operating Training Unit) at [[CFB Bagotville]], tasked with training pilots and navigators for the three operational CAF Voodoo squadrons was renamed No. 410 Squadron. In 1982, No. 410 Squadron made its most recent move to Cold Lake, Alberta, changing aircraft to become the training unit for Canada's new [[CF-18 Hornet]] aircraft.<ref name="RCAF"/><ref name="AWFA"/><br style="clear:both;"/>

== Current ==
=== Operational training ===
No. 410 Squadron is now a [[Canadian Forces Air Command]] aircraft squadron located at [[Canada]]'s primary [[CF-18]] training base, [[CFB Cold Lake|Cold Lake]], [[Alberta]]. The squadron was renamed 410 Tactical Fighter (Operational Training) Squadron, and has had this name since 1982.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.avroland.ca/al-rcaf-com-410sqn.html |title=AvroLand - No. 410 Squadron |accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref> It runs one fighter pilot course every year, training approximately 20 fighter pilots. The training program consists of nine months of ground school, simulator flights, and operational flying. Graduates are taken from the Fighter Lead-In Training Course and are provided with the knowledge of basic skills in both air-to-air and air-to-ground combat. Areas covered in depth include aircraft handling, instrument flight, formation flying, night flying, navigation, air-to-air refuelling, and weapons delivery and tactics. No. 410 Squadron runs the annual Fighter Weapons Instructor Course (FWIC) and a Fighter Electronic Warfare and Advanced Radar (FEWAR) Course. The intense and highly challenging FWIC is three months in length.<ref name="4Wing">{{cite web |url=http://www.airforce.forces.gc.ca/4w-4e/sqns-escs/page-eng.asp?id=478 |title= 4 Wing - No. 410 Squadron General Information |accessdate=25 January 2009 |publisher=[[Canadian Forces]]}}</ref> Each CF-18 squadron and tactical radar squadron sends candidates (eight students per course) who graduate with the leadership qualities and expertise required to return to their operational squadrons and design tactical training programs themselves. The Advanced Radar Course is conducted in two phases, ground school at 4 Wing and a flying phase at an electronic warfare range. This three-week course is designed to graduate ten pilots annually who return to their squadrons as electronic warfare experts and instructors. Since No. 410 Squadron has always had some of the most experienced CF-18 pilots in the fighter community, it is often charged with carrying out special fighter projects.. The Squadron conducted the operational testing and evaluation of the CF's precision guided munitions, and will be testing the use of night vision devices in the Hornet.<ref name="4Wing"/>

==== FOTEF and 2009 ====
A sub-unit of No. 410 Squadron is FOTEF, which is the "Fighter Operational Test & Evaluation Flight". FOTEF is responsible for the operational testing and evaluation to meet the needs of the Fighter Force (FF). Their efforts are to continue to be integral to the operational effectiveness of all aspects of core and CF-18 capabilities. Some the new systems being evaluated are Night Vision Imaging Systems (NVIS), Multi-function Information Distribution Systems (MIDS), the Advanced Multi-role Infra-Red Sensor, and the evaluation of new mission planning software and the Advanced Distributed Combat Training System.<ref name="4Wing"/> Working closely with a variety of key units across the Air Force including the "Aerospace Engineering & Test Establishment" (AETE), FOTEF has enabled the integration of newly modernized CF-18 ECP-583 R2 aircraft into the FF. In 2009, No. 410 Squadron is providing the CF-18 Demonstration Pilot and the air display CF-18 for the year's airshow season. Captain Tim "Donor" Woods, from Dundas, Ontario, was been selected as the year's demonstration pilot and the paint scheme of his air display jet was developed in honour of the "Centennial of Flight" in Canada.<ref name="4Wing"/>

==== Recertification and curriculum ====
The first seven courses the squadron ran were six month full-squadron courses in that the graduating pilots formed new CF-18 squadrons. Following this initial cadre of courses, No. 410 Squadron trained CF-18 pilots at a rate of approximately 50 per year. In 1992, with the closure of three squadrons in Germany, this was reduced to 25. With the recent reduction in size of the remaining operational squadrons, No. 410 Squadron now trains approximately 20 fighter pilots annually.<ref name="4Wing-History">{{cite web |url=http://www.airforce.forces.gc.ca/4w-4e/sqns-escs/page-eng.asp?id=479 |title= 4 Wing - No. 410 Squadron History |accessdate=3 March 2009 |publisher=[[Canadian Forces]]}}</ref> At the same time as the current work mandate, No. 410 Squadron is also responsible for training and recertifying about five former CF-18 Hornet pilots annually. These pilots are returning to the CF-18 cockpit after a ground or exchange tour. Furthermore, No. 410 Squadron also trains newly arrived foreign exchange officers who will be joining one of Canada's two operational fighter squadrons. As backgrounds can differ significantly, each course is tailored to the individual based on their experience and demonstrated competencies.<ref name="4Wing"/> Areas covered in depth in the Fighter Pilot Course (FPC) include basic and advanced aircraft handling, instrument flight, formation flying, night flying, all-weather interception, air-to-air refuelling, Basic Fighter Manoeuvres (BFM - "dogfighting skills") and air combat.<ref name="4Wing"/> The latter half of each FPC comprises academic air-to-ground weapons delivery and Close Air Support (CAS), as well as advanced Air Interdiction (AI) tactics, the former usually completed during a squadron deployment to the south-western United States in the late spring and early fall due to the significantly better weather and the sheer number of bombing ranges available.<ref name="4Wing"/>

=== ''Jetstream'' ===
The television show [[Jetstream (TV series)|''Jetstream'']] was filmed in 2007 with the squadron and showed life on the base and what pilots must endure to become [[fighter pilot]]s. They stayed with 410 for nine months to become fighter pilots and in that time some candidates did not graduate.<ref name=Jet/> The television show was given full access to the candidates lives from ground school to graduation, and was allowed access almost everywhere. The series followed the six members of the Canadian Air Force's "Class of 2006" who had been selected to learn with 410.<ref>{{cite web | title=Paperny launches Discovery Channel series ''Jetstream'' | url =http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/westcoastlife/story.html?id=86b3f50a-84a0-4b92-b2b3-ed5df249d31b | accessdate=06 January 2008}}</ref> The television show called the air base "fighter town", but Cold Lake is one of two bases that primarily use fighter/interceptor aircraft.<ref name=Jet>{{cite web | title=''Jetstream'' | url =http://www.discoverychannel.ca/jetstream/#/utility/about/ |accessdate=13 December 2008}}</ref>

== Aircraft ==
[[File:Mosquito 600pix.jpg|thumb|right|A de Havilland Mosquito]]
=== Second World War ===
No. 410 Squadron RCAF began its flying career by flying the [[T-6 Texan|North American Harvard]] training aircraft. The Harvard was a single-engine advanced trainer aircraft designed by North American Aviation, used to train fighter pilots.<ref>Becker, 12</ref> The fighter that was first used was the [[Boulton Paul]] Defiant NFI during July 1941 to May 1942. The Boulton Paul Defiant was a "turret fighter" that was used as a night fighter by No. 410 Squadron. The main problem with this aircraft was that it had no forward armament,<ref>Brew, 46</ref> and so was exchanged for the [[Bristol Aeroplane Company|Bristol]] [[Bristol Beaufighter|Beaufighter]] II, which was used during April 1942 up until January 1943. The Beaufighter was a British long-range heavy fighter. The Mk II used the [[Rolls Royce Merlin]] engine for better power than the original Beaufighter.<ref>Eden, 68</ref> Later that year No. 410 changed to the de Havilland Mosquito Mk II in November 1942 through December 1943. Afterward the Squadron only used the Mosquito. It used the variants VI (July 1943 - September 1943), XIII (December 1943 - August 1944), and XXX (August 1944 - June 1945). All of these fighters had the same basic design, that of a low to medium altitude daytime tactical bomber, high altitude night bomber, [[pathfinder (RAF)|pathfinder]], [[day fighter|day]] or [[night fighter]], [[fighter-bomber]], intruder, maritime strike and [[photo reconnaissance]] aircraft.<ref>Eden, 118-129</ref>

=== Post War ===
As a trainer 410 used the [[Canadair]] [[Canadair T-33|CT-133 Silver Star]], a derivative of the [[T-33 Shooting Star]]. The Silver Star was a  jet trainer aircraft that was powered with the [[Rolls Royce Nene|Rolls Royce Nene 10]] [[turbojet]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.warbirddepot.com/aircraft_jets_t33-keppeler.asp |title= Canadair T-33 Silver Star | accessdate=13 January 2009}}</ref> After the Second World War No. 410 Squadron began flying the [[de Havilland]] [[de Havilland Vampire|Vampire]]. The Vampire was the second jet-powered aircraft commissioned by the Royal Air Force. It was used as a trainer aircraft that was easy to use.<ref>Watkins, 58</ref> 410 then reestablished the fighter force with the [[Canadair Sabre|Sabre]], which was one of the finest [[dogfighter]]s of its day.<ref name="Milberry">Milberry, 127</ref> The Canadair Sabre was a fighter aircraft that was designed to combat the early MiG fighters. Although the RAAF and the SAAF had trouble ordering the Sabre, because they were built in Canada by Canadair, under license, Canada was able to purchase them with relative ease. With the Korean War the initial batch of ten aircraft was increased to 100.<ref name="Milberry"/> Following the Sabre was the CF-100 Canuck, which came into service in 1953. The [[CF-100 Canuck]], (affectionately known as the Clunk), was a Canadian jet fighter that was the only Canadian designed fighter aircraft that went into mass production. The CF-100 was equipped with an advanced radar and fire control system and so was used as Canada's primary interceptor.<ref>Page</ref> On 20 December 1961 410 became Canada's first operational [[CF-101 Voodoo]] squadron. The Voodoo was an all-weather interceptor aircraft. The Voodoo's primary armament was nuclear [[AIR-2 Genie|AIR-2A Genie]] unguided air-to-air rockets and was used as Canada's primary means of air defence.

=== Current ===
[[File:CF-18 Hornet grounded.jpg|thumb|A CF-18 Hornet]]
No. 410 Squadron RCAF is currently equipped with the [[CF-18 Hornet]]. The first two CF-18 were formally handed over to 410 (Operational Training Unit) Squadron at [[CFB Cold Lake]], Alberta on 25 October 1982.<ref>Spick</ref> The [[McDonnell Douglas]] CF-18 Hornet (CF-188) is a Canadian Forces aircraft, based on the American F/A-18 Hornet. The most visible difference between a CF-18 and a US F-18 is the 600,000 candela night identification light. This spotlight is mounted in the gun loading door on the port side of the aircraft.<ref name=hornet>Jenkins</ref> Some CF-18s have the light temporarily removed, but the window is always in place. Also, the underside of the CF-18 features a painted "dummy canopy". This is intended to disorient and confuse an enemy in air-to-air combat. Many features that made the F/A-18 suitable for naval carrier operations were also retained by the Canadian Forces, such as the robust landing gear, the arrestor hook, and wing-folding mechanisms, which proved useful when operating the fighters from smaller airfields such as those found in the Arctic.<ref name=hornet/>

